Overall, TLDR; ignore the posts clamouring about the difficulty of this game if it's putting you off. Combat is tricky, as it always is; but the overarching brutal difficulty of Souls games has been massively tuned back though huge quality of life changes.
Best game since BBorne.

Killed him in one pull using a Spirit Summon I found, and my upgraded Uchigatana. And then it opened up the path further for me to progress in that direction; because I had the freedom to go where I chose.

In Elden Ring, I got to the first major boss and hit a wall (the wall was I was fucking plastered drunk). So I just turned around and went the other way.
I found dungeons, world bosses, a portal that took me to a terrifying Bloodborne esque area. And then I went back to kill him.

In Souls games, you would often hit a Wall boss. A boss that you just couldn't progress past, be it for your own skill, gear, build, whatever. And it is frustrating, since the pathways unlocked by that boss would allow you to branch off in your journey. But only after it dies.

And finally, the thing that makes the game so so so good if you're new to this series of games; if you get stuck in an area or on a particularly hard boss? Just turn around and walk somewhere else. You have complete freedom over your journey in this game.

This probably comes with me applying the rules of previous games to a new game; like people who complained about blocking doing nothing in Sekiro, when they moved everything to Parrying. Or Bloodborne emphasising aggression over defence (no shields). But mounts feel too cheesy.

When I first got my ass clapped by the Tree Spirit, I understood I would have to come back later with more levels and gear under my belt.
I didn't expect however I could return literally 30 minutes later and just drive by him repeatedly on a lightning fast horse.

3rd thing in the game; mounted combat.
I actually really dislike this. I absolutely LOVE being able to mount up and explore the world, and again it would be insanely tedious to make your way around without it; but mounted combat trivialises nearly every outdoor encounter.

This Is The Power Known Only To Others As
A D H D https://t.co/ctyi46gxyJ

I do NOT think this is a bad thing. I think it makes the game so much more approachable to newcomers, and potentially makes the game a cakewalk for Souls veterans.
The combat with bosses is as slick and challenging as before; you now however don't have the game fighting you too.
This is the distance between the nearest Grace and the second main boss of Elden Ring. You turn right out of Grace room, and the boss door is there. https://t.co/G485e8EaOF

This is the distance between the nearest Bonfire and the first main boss of Dark Souls 3. The Bonfire is in the top left. The boss is in the bottom right. The runback for this boss is honestly pretty typical for this game, not even remotely the longest. https://t.co/TgsSAZx7C3

Number 2 being Graces; there are honestly too many. Big complaint of Dark Souls 3 was the proliferation of Bonfires; this game is like they had a ALL BONFIRES MUST go sale. It makes complete sense with it being an openworld game, for ease of travel but please hear me out.

Number 1 being Statues; having Statues exist in areas that have punishing enemies is an absolutely huge quality of life change especially in an open world game.
Running into an area way above your expected level, getting one shot by a spirit, and respawning nearby? Huge.

Biggest thing in this game in terms of difficulty adjustment is the Bonfire runback. There's two things that make this an absolute easy mode in comparison to prior games, and I do NOT think it's a bad thing for accessibility in this game.
Number 1 is Statues, Number 2 is Graces.

One or two good songs, and it was listenable all the way through but like... it just doesn't hit the same.=

I would say that if you're a fan of other Souls games, and you've become accustomed to the difficulty imposed specifically by the systems of those games, this game will feel like an absolute breeze in terms of character progression and gameplay.

This is by far the best Soulsborne game to get into if you have ever been put off by the difficulty of Fromsoft games before.
I cannot stress to you how insanely more accessible this game is. I'm not saying this as a good player, I'm actually bad at Souls games. Like real bad.
